---
import WebsiteLayout from '../../../layouts/WebsiteLayout.astro';

const title = "Perfume: The Story of a Murderer";
const author = "Patrick Süskind";
const pubYear = "1985";
const rating = 4;
const slug = "perfume";
---

<WebsiteLayout>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <title>{title} by {author} - Book Review</title>
    <meta name="description" content={`Review of "${title}" by ${author}. Rating: ${rating}/5 stars.`} />
    <!-- Open Graph / Facebook -->
    <meta property="og:type" content="article" />
    <meta property="og:url" content={Astro.url.href} />
    <meta property="og:title" content={`${title} by ${author}`} />
    <meta property="og:description" content={`Review of "${title}" by ${author}. Rating: ${rating}/5 stars.`} />
    <!-- Twitter -->
    <meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image" />
    <meta name="twitter:url" content={Astro.url.href} />
    <meta name="twitter:title" content={`${title} by ${author}`} />
    <meta name="twitter:description" content={`Review of "${title}" by ${author}. Rating: ${rating}/5 stars.`} />
  </Fragment>

  <article class="book-review-content">
    <div class="book-header">
      <div class="book-meta">
        <h1 class="book-title">{title}</h1>
        <p class="book-author">By {author}</p>
        <p class="book-year">Published: {pubYear}</p>
        <div class="book-rating">
          {Array.from({ length: 5 }).map((_, i) => (
            <span class={`star ${i < rating ? 'filled' : ''}`}>★</span>
          ))}
          <span class="rating-text">{rating}/5</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="book-summary-section">
      <h2>Summary</h2>
      <p>
        A dark and atmospheric novel about Jean-Baptiste Grenouille, a man born with an extraordinary sense 
        of smell but no personal scent of his own. Set in 18th-century France, the story follows Grenouille's 
        obsession with capturing the perfect scent, leading him down a path of murder and madness. Süskind's 
        prose is rich and evocative, creating a world where scent becomes a form of power and identity. The 
        novel explores themes of alienation, obsession, and the nature of human connection through a unique 
        and unsettling lens.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="review-section">
      <button class="review-toggle" id="review-toggle">
        <span class="toggle-text">Show Review</span>
        <span class="toggle-icon">▼</span>
      </button>
      <div class="book-review-collapsible" id="review-content">
        <h2>My Review</h2>
        <p>
          <em>Perfume</em> is a masterclass in sensory writing. Süskind creates an entire world through 
          smell—a feat that seems almost impossible given how difficult it is to describe scents. The novel 
          is both beautiful and deeply disturbing, a combination that makes it unforgettable.
        </p>
        
        <h3>The Power of Scent</h3>
        <p>
          What makes this book remarkable is how Süskind uses scent as a lens to explore human nature. 
          Grenouille's superhuman olfactory abilities allow him to perceive the world in ways others cannot, 
          but his lack of personal scent makes him invisible, inhuman. This paradox drives the entire narrative: 
          he can understand others through their scents, but they cannot understand him because he has none.
        </p>
        
        <p>
          The descriptions of smells throughout the book are extraordinary. Süskind doesn't just tell you 
          something smells good or bad—he creates entire olfactory landscapes. The stench of 18th-century 
          Paris, the delicate fragrances of flowers, the complex scents of human beings—all of it is rendered 
          with precision and poetry.
        </p>
        
        <h3>Grenouille as Anti-Hero</h3>
        <p>
          Grenouille is one of literature's most compelling monsters. He's not evil in the traditional sense—he 
          lacks empathy, but he also lacks malice. He's driven by a pure, almost aesthetic obsession. His 
          murders aren't acts of rage or hatred; they're acts of collection, like a butterfly collector 
          pinning specimens. This makes him more disturbing than a conventional villain.
        </p>
        
        <p>
          The novel raises uncomfortable questions about art, obsession, and the price of perfection. Grenouille's 
          quest for the perfect scent leads him to commit atrocities, but the final perfume he creates has 
          transformative power. Is the art worth the cost? Süskind doesn't provide easy answers.
        </p>
        
        <h3>Atmosphere & Setting</h3>
        <p>
          The 18th-century setting is perfectly realized. Süskind captures the filth and beauty of pre-revolutionary 
          France, the contrast between the opulent world of perfumers and the squalor of the streets. The 
          historical detail feels authentic without being overwhelming—it serves the story rather than 
          dominating it.
        </p>
        
        <h3>What Didn't Work</h3>
        <p>
          The novel's pacing can be slow at times, particularly in the middle sections. Some readers might 
          find Grenouille's lack of humanity makes him difficult to connect with, though I think this is 
          intentional. The ending, while powerful, is also deeply unsettling—it's not for everyone.
        </p>
        
        <h3>Final Thoughts</h3>
        <p>
          <em>Perfume</em> is a unique and powerful novel that uses an unusual premise to explore universal 
          themes. It's beautifully written, thought-provoking, and deeply disturbing. Süskind's ability to 
          create a world through scent alone is a remarkable achievement. While it's not a book I'd recommend 
          to everyone (due to its dark themes), it's one that will stay with you long after you finish it.
        </p>
        
        <p>
          The novel works on multiple levels: as a psychological thriller, as a meditation on art and obsession, 
          and as a sensory experiment in literature. It's a book that challenges you to think about what makes 
          us human and what happens when someone exists outside that definition.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="related-section">
      <h2>Related Reading</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Umberto Eco - <em>The Name of the Rose</em> (atmospheric historical fiction)</li>
        <li>Mary Shelley - <em>Frankenstein</em> (themes of creation and monstrosity)</li>
        <li>Thomas Mann - <em>Death in Venice</em> (obsession and aestheticism)</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <div class="back-link">
      <a href="/books/have-read">← Back to Books I've Read</a>
    </div>
  </article>
</WebsiteLayout>

<style>
  .book-review-content {
    max-width: 800px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    font-family: 'Georgia', serif;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: #1a1a1a;
    padding: 2rem 1rem;
  }

  .book-header {
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
    padding-bottom: 2rem;
    border-bottom: 2px solid #e5e7eb;
  }

  .book-meta {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }

  .book-title {
    font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
    font-size: 2.25rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: #0f172a;
    margin: 0;
    line-height: 1.2;
  }

  .book-author {
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    font-style: italic;
    color: #4b5563;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .book-year {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    color: #6b7280;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .book-rating {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.5rem;
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
  }

  .star {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    color: #e5e7eb;
    transition: color 0.2s ease;
  }

  .star.filled {
    color: #facc15;
  }

  .rating-text {
    font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: #4b5563;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin-left: 0.5rem;
  }

  .book-review-content section {
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }

  .book-review-content h2 {
    font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
    font-size: 1.75rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: #0f172a;
    margin: 2.5rem 0 1.25rem 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #e5e7eb;
    padding-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .book-review-content h3 {
    font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
    font-size: 1.35rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: #1a1a1a;
    margin: 2rem 0 1rem 0;
  }

  .book-review-content p {
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    text-align: left;
  }

  .book-review-content ul {
    list-style-type: disc;
    margin-left: 2rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  .book-review-content li {
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .review-section {
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }

  .review-toggle {
    width: 100%;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: center;
    padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
    background: #f9fafb;
    border: 2px solid #e5e7eb;
    border-radius: 8px;
    cursor: pointer;
    font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: #0f172a;
    font-weight: 600;
    transition: all 0.2s ease;
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .review-toggle:hover {
    background: #f3f4f6;
    border-color: #cbd5e1;
  }

  .review-toggle.active {
    border-bottom-left-radius: 0;
    border-bottom-right-radius: 0;
    border-bottom: none;
  }

  .toggle-icon {
    transition: transform 0.3s ease;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: #6b7280;
  }

  .review-toggle.active .toggle-icon {
    transform: rotate(180deg);
  }

  .book-review-collapsible {
    max-height: 0;
    overflow: hidden;
    transition: max-height 0.4s ease, padding 0.4s ease, margin 0.4s ease;
    padding: 0 1.25rem;
    margin: 0;
    background: #f9fafb;
    border: 2px solid #e5e7eb;
    border-top: none;
    border-radius: 0 0 8px 8px;
  }

  .book-review-collapsible.expanded {
    max-height: 5000px;
    padding: 2rem 1.25rem;
    margin-top: 0;
  }

  .book-review-collapsible h2 {
    margin-top: 0;
  }

  .back-link {
    margin-top: 3rem;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid #e5e7eb;
  }

  .back-link a {
    color: #2b6cb0;
    text-decoration: none;
    font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
    font-weight: 500;
    transition: color 0.2s ease;
  }

  .back-link a:hover {
    color: #1e40af;
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  @media (max-width: 800px) {
    .book-review-content {
      padding: 1.5rem 1rem;
    }

    .book-title {
      font-size: 1.75rem;
    }

    .book-author {
      font-size: 1rem;
    }

    .book-review-content h2 {
      font-size: 1.5rem;
    }

    .book-review-content h3 {
      font-size: 1.2rem;
    }

    .book-review-collapsible.expanded {
      padding: 1.5rem 1rem;
    }
  }
</style>

<script>
  document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    const toggle = document.getElementById('review-toggle');
    const content = document.getElementById('review-content');
    
    if (toggle && content) {
      toggle.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const isExpanded = content.classList.contains('expanded');
        
        if (isExpanded) {
          content.classList.remove('expanded');
          toggle.classList.remove('active');
          toggle.querySelector('.toggle-text').textContent = 'Show Review';
        } else {
          content.classList.add('expanded');
          toggle.classList.add('active');
          toggle.querySelector('.toggle-text').textContent = 'Hide Review';
        }
      });
    }
  });
</script>




